WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.592 --> 00:00:03.175
(bright music)

2
00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:11.070
<v Host>Always a good day is Dr. Garry, though.</v>

3
00:00:11.070 --> 00:00:14.760
He's gonna take over now as we talk about fracture care.

4
00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:15.873
Thank you, Joseph.

5
00:00:17.010 --> 00:00:18.720
<v ->Thank you, David.</v>

6
00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:22.350
Okay, so we're gonna talk about some pediatric fractures

7
00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:24.510
and then adult fractures.

8
00:00:24.510 --> 00:00:27.690
I would, for those of you that,

9
00:00:27.690 --> 00:00:30.600
particularly who are gonna take the exam,

10
00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:33.540
please pay attention to the supplemental slides

11
00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:37.290
about complications of bracing and casting

12
00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:40.143
as well as stress fractures, okay?

13
00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:43.500
All right, so let's get started.

14
00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:48.450
If I'm concerned about a fracture, my first line is X-rays,

15
00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:50.370
and generally I want three views

16
00:00:50.370 --> 00:00:53.040
to be able to identify what's going on,

17
00:00:53.040 --> 00:00:58.040
an AP, a lateral, and an oblique in general terms.

18
00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:03.500
My second line is non-contrast MRI for fracture assessment

19
00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:06.060
if that's what I need.

20
00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:10.110
There's a caveat to that and that's a non-contrast CT.

21
00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:13.290
So in two fracture types,

22
00:01:13.290 --> 00:01:17.700
I want a non-contrast CT as my second line.

23
00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:22.380
Intra-articular distal radial fracture that's displaced.

24
00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:24.450
So I see that on X-ray.

25
00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:26.970
I want to be able to get a better idea

26
00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:30.360
of the degree of displacement of that

27
00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:33.960
and a tibial plateau fracture, okay?

28
00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:36.630
These, they're prone to

29
00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:39.600
developing osteoarthritis post-fracture.

30
00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:44.600
So I want to optimize my treatment of those

31
00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:48.150
and surgical decisions will be made based on the CT.

32
00:01:48.150 --> 00:01:49.920
So if you're concerned about it,

33
00:01:49.920 --> 00:01:54.240
get the CT as you're referring them to the orthopedist,

34
00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.640
if that would be your next step,

35
00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:58.590
so that they have all the information

36
00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:00.240
at the time they see the patient.

37
00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:03.390
Pediatric fractures,

38
00:02:03.390 --> 00:02:06.960
roughly 1/3 of them are gonna involve the growth plate.

39
00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:10.260
Roughly 1/3 of them are gonna involve the fingers.

40
00:02:10.260 --> 00:02:12.510
And it's relatively uncommon

41
00:02:12.510 --> 00:02:15.000
that you're gonna have a growth deformity

42
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.500
as a result of a pediatric fracture.

43
00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.410
Again, if you suspect a fracture,

44
00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:25.770
get radiographs in this population

45
00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:28.560
primarily because of the open physis.

46
00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:30.840
We're gonna see a bit of a caveat about that

47
00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:32.913
when we talk about the ankle.

48
00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:38.340
And then they always like to ask

49
00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:40.980
some kind of question about

50
00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:44.760
you have some intra-articular fracture in this 8-year-old

51
00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:49.170
or 7-year-old or 12-year-old

52
00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:53.760
and that intra-articular fracture is gonna be displaced.

53
00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:55.770
So what are you gonna do with it?

54
00:02:55.770 --> 00:02:58.080
Well, again, because we're trying

55
00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:03.080
to preserve the joint in pediatric and adolescent patients,

56
00:03:03.300 --> 00:03:05.640
particularly with open growth plates,

57
00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:09.330
we're almost always going to have an open reduction

58
00:03:09.330 --> 00:03:10.710
and internal fixation

59
00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:14.160
for any displaced intra-articular fracture.

60
00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:17.820
Whether it's the toe, whether it's the hand,

61
00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:21.483
the elbow, the knee, wherever it may be.

62
00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:25.590
Here are your Salter-Harris classifications.

63
00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:29.250
Remember type one is a fracture through the physis.

64
00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.910
Type two is the most common type.

65
00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:35.430
I would pay attention to that most common type

66
00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:36.720
that you're gonna see

67
00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:40.350
through the physis and then up into the metaphysis.

68
00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:44.430
Type three and four are intra-articular.

69
00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:47.730
So these almost always end up at a surgeon

70
00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:51.180
because they're gonna need a pin or a wire in them

71
00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:53.040
to optimize the joint.

72
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.073
And then type five is a crush injury.

73
00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:01.260
Okay, so let's go into some specific fractures

74
00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:04.020
and specific things I want you to pay attention to.

75
00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:05.943
The supracondylar fracture,

76
00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.420
five to seven or eight-year olds,

77
00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:11.340
they fall on an outstretched hand.

78
00:04:11.340 --> 00:04:13.440
We call that a FOOSH injury.

79
00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.690
We're gonna see a lot of that in this talk.

80
00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:18.573
So I'm just gonna refer to it as FOOSH injuries.

81
00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:23.040
These kids are gonna present usually with a painful elbow.

82
00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:24.330
They don't want to move it,

83
00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:27.330
and they may have already ecchymosis, tenderness,

84
00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:29.883
and or swelling in the antecubital fossa.

85
00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:34.980
You'll get your radiographs to look for this.

86
00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:39.980
If you have anything other than a non-displaced fracture,

87
00:04:40.080 --> 00:04:41.820
that would be a type one.

88
00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:44.880
Anything else by general standards

89
00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.420
will be referred to an orthopedic surgeon, okay?

90
00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:51.033
Any kind of displacement would get referred.

91
00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:55.230
In my experience, most family medicine physicians

92
00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:56.490
aren't really all that comfortable

93
00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:59.670
taking care of supracondylar fractures period,

94
00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:02.100
even if they're completely non-displaced.

95
00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:06.240
But if it is non-displaced, put 'em in a long arm cast,

96
00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:09.450
recheck them in one week, and then three weeks.

97
00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:12.060
Again, as long as they remain non-displaced,

98
00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:13.500
they can be treated.

99
00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.240
What I want you to pay attention to

100
00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:20.160
is the most commonly entrapped nerve

101
00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:21.720
in a supracondylar fracture

102
00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:24.900
is the anterior interosseous nerve, okay?

103
00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:26.940
That overlaps with the median nerve

104
00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:29.460
so that if they can make an okay sign,

105
00:05:29.460 --> 00:05:32.163
the anterior interosseous nerve is intact.

106
00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:39.630
On your lateral film of the elbow, you have fat pads.

107
00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:41.790
And remember, you see the outline

108
00:05:41.790 --> 00:05:43.770
of the anterior fat pad here.

109
00:05:43.770 --> 00:05:46.980
It's the blacker shading

110
00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.640
because there's fluid in the joint,

111
00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:53.277
and so it pushes the capsule out anteriorly.

112
00:05:53.277 --> 00:05:55.800
And so you get this darkness

113
00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:00.800
or this black, degree of blackness anteriorly.

114
00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:03.180
That's suggestive of a fracture.

115
00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:06.300
If I see that on a plain film, I'm thinking, okay,

116
00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:09.750
maybe an intra-articular fracture involved here.

117
00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:12.960
If the posterior fat pad is involved,

118
00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:16.080
and here I see the posterior fat pad,

119
00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:19.590
that blackness should be adherent

120
00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:22.320
to the posterior humerus, but it's not.

121
00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:25.170
It's migrating out posteriorly

122
00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:27.150
because there's fluid in the joint,

123
00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:28.770
then that's really pathognomonic

124
00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:30.360
of an intra-articular fracture.

125
00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:33.930
So I need to treat them as a fracture,

126
00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:36.930
even though I don't see it on my radiographs.

127
00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:39.720
I bring them back in a week, and I repeat my radiographs,

128
00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:42.750
and there's that supracondylar fracture, okay?

129
00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:46.410
So now you can either decide you're gonna treat this

130
00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:49.683
if it's a type one, or you're gonna refer them on.

131
00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:56.010
In pediatrics, in an acute elbow injury,

132
00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:59.700
if they're unable to extend the elbow fully,

133
00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:02.670
that is associated with elbow fractures.

134
00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:04.023
So be aware of that.

135
00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:08.130
Here's a buckle or torus fracture.

136
00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:11.790
This is about 50% of all wrist fractures that occur.

137
00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:12.623
What's new?

138
00:07:12.623 --> 00:07:13.980
You've all seen this.

139
00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:15.003
What's new?

140
00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:19.830
Assuming I have a reliable parent, okay,

141
00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:21.540
this is what you're gonna do.

142
00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:23.850
You put 'em in a soft wrist splint,

143
00:07:23.850 --> 00:07:25.920
you tell 'em to keep that on for three weeks.

144
00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:30.363
In three weeks, the parent just palpates the area.

145
00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:35.820
If the kid's okay, take off the splint and let 'em go, okay?

146
00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:37.920
There is no return to the office.

147
00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.200
There is no repeat radiographs,

148
00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:44.343
there is no casting that's involved, okay?

149
00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:46.133
That is new.

150
00:07:46.133 --> 00:07:49.650
And you see the choosing wisely with the data

151
00:07:49.650 --> 00:07:51.250
that's come out on that now too.

152
00:07:52.380 --> 00:07:54.033
Okay, so our first question.

153
00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.390
A 3-year-old male is brought to your office by his mother

154
00:07:57.390 --> 00:07:58.950
to evaluate his left arm,

155
00:07:58.950 --> 00:08:00.810
which he stopped using earlier today

156
00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:04.230
after walking home with his mother from preschool.

157
00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:06.210
He cries when the elbow is manipulated

158
00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:07.980
and keeps his left arm at his side.

159
00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.950
Elbow radiographs are negative for fracture.

160
00:08:10.950 --> 00:08:13.890
Using an evidence-based approach to your patient,

161
00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:17.793
which would be the most successful initial treatment.

162
00:08:22.830 --> 00:08:25.882
Okay, hyperpronation, terrific.

163
00:08:25.882 --> 00:08:30.882
Flexion supination is what 60% of us in here

164
00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:36.120
probably learned when we were training.

165
00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:39.660
Now hyperpronation is what can be used.

166
00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:42.120
This is nursemaid's elbow.

167
00:08:42.120 --> 00:08:43.770
Remember, these are your toddlers.

168
00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:46.740
It's a traction injury to the elbow.

169
00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:49.170
Typically when you're holding the hand,

170
00:08:49.170 --> 00:08:50.670
pulling the toddler toward you

171
00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:53.470
or keeping them from running off someplace

172
00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:59.160
and you support the elbow, take the hand,

173
00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:01.090
and pronate it all the way over

174
00:09:02.325 --> 00:09:03.870
while you're supporting the elbow,

175
00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:05.880
and you can feel the radial head,

176
00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:07.170
and you get all the way over,

177
00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:10.920
and you'll feel it pop right back in, okay?

178
00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:12.930
That's first line treatment.

179
00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:16.950
And frankly is easier for someone who's done both.

180
00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.223
Many times the hyperpronation is a lot easier.

181
00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:26.490
Clavicle is the most commonly fractured bone in the body,

182
00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:30.030
and virtually all of these occur in the middle third.

183
00:09:30.030 --> 00:09:34.680
So what you want to do

184
00:09:34.680 --> 00:09:37.410
is you're gonna put individuals in a sling.

185
00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:39.840
You do not need to put them in a figure eight.

186
00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.060
You can,

187
00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:43.800
you do not need to

188
00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:45.750
because the outcomes are equivalent

189
00:09:45.750 --> 00:09:49.140
whether you put an individual in a figure of eight

190
00:09:49.140 --> 00:09:52.650
or you put them in a sling, okay?

191
00:09:52.650 --> 00:09:54.543
So sling is generally preferred.

192
00:09:55.977 --> 00:09:58.124
Okay, our next question.

193
00:09:58.124 --> 00:10:01.500
A 44-year-old female tripped and fell on the ice

194
00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:04.980
on an outstretched left hand, another FOOSH injury.

195
00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:07.310
She presents with this radiograph.

196
00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:15.870
So the question is,

197
00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:18.933
what is the most commonly injured nerve in this injury?

198
00:10:21.088 --> 00:10:25.793
Is it musculocutaneous, median, radial, or ulnar nerve?

199
00:10:32.613 --> 00:10:34.293
Okay good, median.

200
00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:40.440
Not radial, but let's talk about what we have,

201
00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:42.330
a distal radial fracture.

202
00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:47.250
So roughly one in five fractures that we see in adults

203
00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:50.013
are distal radial fractures.

204
00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:54.810
Far and away the most common etiology

205
00:10:54.810 --> 00:10:56.433
is osteoporosis.

206
00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:02.163
So we should just define a fragility fracture.

207
00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:06.330
Fragility fracture is one of the,

208
00:11:06.330 --> 00:11:11.330
a fragility fracture in a postmenopausal female

209
00:11:11.460 --> 00:11:16.460
or a male over 70 is a clinical diagnostic indicator

210
00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:18.693
for osteoporosis.

211
00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:23.970
A fragility fracture is,

212
00:11:23.970 --> 00:11:26.340
I'm walking down the street,

213
00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:31.340
and I trip, and I fall, and I put my hand out, okay?

214
00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:36.453
If I'm 25, and I break my wrist, I broke my wrist.

215
00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:41.010
If I'm a postmenopausal female or a male over 70,

216
00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:43.860
and I do that, it's a fragility fracture.

217
00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:48.600
It's a fracture that occurs from a standing height.

218
00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:52.590
I did not fall off a ladder, I did not fall off the roof.

219
00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:56.490
I did not fall out of my deer stand

220
00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:58.830
or wherever I was.

221
00:11:58.830 --> 00:12:01.950
There's no trauma, so to speak, that's involved

222
00:12:01.950 --> 00:12:05.580
short of falling from a standing height.

223
00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:09.000
So that's our diagnosis of fragility fracture.

224
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.410
It's important because you're gonna see a theme here

225
00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:17.520
about assessment of bone health for individuals.

226
00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:21.030
It's important because if I have that history,

227
00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:23.763
I want an assessment of bone health.

228
00:12:25.271 --> 00:12:27.060
DXA, okay?

229
00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:29.760
All right, so for these,

230
00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:34.020
median nerve is the most commonly involved nerve entrapment

231
00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:35.970
that occurs with distal radial fractures.

232
00:12:35.970 --> 00:12:39.840
And remember, if I have an intra-articular fracture,

233
00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:43.260
and it appears that I have even one to two millimeters

234
00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:47.160
of displacement along the articular surface,

235
00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:49.143
I want a non-contrast CT.

236
00:12:50.010 --> 00:12:52.140
I can get the non-contrast CT.

237
00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:55.290
And if I think, you know, I'm not comfortable handling this,

238
00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:57.000
I'm gonna send it on to the orthopedic surgeon,

239
00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.570
get the non-contrast CT before their appointment,

240
00:13:00.570 --> 00:13:02.730
so that they can make the decision

241
00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:04.180
because that's the next step.

242
00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:09.120
Okay, and this I would give to you,

243
00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:12.750
this is gonna be covered elsewhere this week,

244
00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:16.473
but I would give you this to print off and study.

245
00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:20.340
There are oftentimes lots of questions

246
00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:23.490
with regards to innervation of the hand itself.

247
00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:25.200
So you have that.

248
00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:26.280
Okay, our next question.

249
00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:28.500
A 36-year-old female presents to your office

250
00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:31.050
and reports that she had a FOOSH injury

251
00:13:31.050 --> 00:13:33.720
in the left hand three days ago,

252
00:13:33.720 --> 00:13:35.340
presents with left wrist pain,

253
00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:37.550
minor swelling in this radiograph.

254
00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.523
So take a look at it, and then I'll ask you a question.

255
00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:51.393
Okay, what's the best treatment option?

256
00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:56.580
You're gonna refer her for surgical fixation,

257
00:13:56.580 --> 00:14:00.270
put her in a volar wrist splint for eight weeks,

258
00:14:00.270 --> 00:14:03.180
a short arm cast for eight weeks,

259
00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:06.663
or a thumb spica cast for eight weeks.

260
00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:14.610
Good, thumb spica cast.

261
00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:17.460
So right, this individual had

262
00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:22.460
a non-displaced scaphoid fracture of the,

263
00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:24.660
we would call this the waist

264
00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:27.660
of the waist of the scaphoid fracture.

265
00:14:27.660 --> 00:14:30.270
So in terms of scaphoid fractures,

266
00:14:30.270 --> 00:14:32.970
yes, they occur with FOOSH injuries.

267
00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:36.780
Yes, I generally have minor swelling, but I have pain.

268
00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:41.050
Remember that I am tender in the anatomical snuff box

269
00:14:42.270 --> 00:14:45.810
and my initial radiographs may well be negative,

270
00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:48.930
and if they are but I suspect this,

271
00:14:48.930 --> 00:14:50.130
then I must put them

272
00:14:50.130 --> 00:14:55.130
in some kind of thumb spica splint, cast, something,

273
00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:01.290
to immobilize that area, and then bring them back

274
00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:05.730
and repeat radiographs in one to two weeks.

275
00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:10.500
And remember that the scaphoid blood supply

276
00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:13.200
is distal to proximal.

277
00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:17.220
So I really like those distal fractures

278
00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:18.960
because they heal more quickly.

279
00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:23.960
They have a lower tendency to non-union, they do better.

280
00:15:24.090 --> 00:15:26.550
The proximal fractures are the ones

281
00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:29.460
that have a higher propensity to non-union

282
00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:33.570
and higher propensity toward avascular necrosis.

283
00:15:33.570 --> 00:15:34.533
That's a problem.

284
00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:40.230
Okay, no clear benefit to operative intervention

285
00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:43.290
of an acute non-displaced scaphoid fracture.

286
00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:45.480
But if I do have some displacement,

287
00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:48.810
I want to get them referred to surgery

288
00:15:48.810 --> 00:15:53.810
because fixation is really the faster recovery method.

289
00:15:54.330 --> 00:15:57.510
It's simply, it's a tiny little incision

290
00:15:57.510 --> 00:15:58.833
and a screw that goes in.

291
00:16:00.433 --> 00:16:03.300
It's less than a 15 minute surgery, right?

292
00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:05.580
It takes an hour to get 'em into the OR,

293
00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:07.680
it takes 'em 10 minutes to do the surgery.

294
00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:12.120
It takes 'em one or two hours in recovery when they're done.

295
00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:13.663
Okay, so our next question,

296
00:16:13.663 --> 00:16:16.110
a 17-year-old football player comes to clinic

297
00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:17.280
the morning after a game

298
00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:20.970
in which he injured the ring finger of his right hand.

299
00:16:20.970 --> 00:16:23.070
He grabbed the jersey of an opposing player

300
00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:23.903
as he tackled him

301
00:16:23.903 --> 00:16:26.790
and immediately felt pain in the distal aspect

302
00:16:26.790 --> 00:16:28.230
of the affected finger.

303
00:16:28.230 --> 00:16:30.750
On examination, there's mild swelling of the finger,

304
00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:34.830
and he cannot flex at the distal interphalangeal joint.

305
00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:38.430
Radiographs show a small bony fragment

306
00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:43.430
at the volar surface of the proximal distal phalanx.

307
00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:45.390
So our question,

308
00:16:45.390 --> 00:16:49.770
which of the following is the most appropriate management

309
00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:51.780
for this individual?

310
00:16:51.780 --> 00:16:54.303
Are you gonna refer him to a hand surgeon?

311
00:16:55.260 --> 00:16:56.190
Are you gonna splint

312
00:16:56.190 --> 00:16:58.620
the distal interphalangeal joint in flexion

313
00:16:58.620 --> 00:16:59.793
for eight weeks,

314
00:17:01.050 --> 00:17:03.330
splint the distal interphalangeal joint

315
00:17:03.330 --> 00:17:06.123
in extension for eight weeks,

316
00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:09.810
or splint the proximal interphalangeal joint

317
00:17:09.810 --> 00:17:11.280
in extension for six weeks,

318
00:17:11.280 --> 00:17:15.213
followed by night splinting for another four to six weeks.

319
00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:25.110
Okay, so about half of you want to send to the hand surgeon,

320
00:17:25.110 --> 00:17:26.463
which would be correct.

321
00:17:27.750 --> 00:17:32.750
We're gonna move right on into another finger question.

322
00:17:35.712 --> 00:17:37.320
A 33-year-old male presents

323
00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:39.510
with suspected dislocated finger.

324
00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:41.280
He was playing volleyball the previous day

325
00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:44.190
when he jammed his left fifth finger.

326
00:17:44.190 --> 00:17:46.830
On examination, the distal interphalangeal joint

327
00:17:46.830 --> 00:17:51.000
to the left fifth digit has full passive range of motion,

328
00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.730
but he cannot actively extend the distal phalanx.

329
00:17:53.730 --> 00:17:56.070
A radiograph of the digit is normal.

330
00:17:56.070 --> 00:17:59.190
Which of the following is now most appropriate

331
00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:00.543
for this individual?

332
00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.620
Okay, terrific, so we got these, all right,

333
00:18:10.620 --> 00:18:12.360
and we'll just briefly talk.

334
00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:14.610
The first one was jersey finger.

335
00:18:14.610 --> 00:18:18.270
It's an avulsion of the flexor digitorum profundus tendon.

336
00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:19.530
It's a flexor tendon.

337
00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:24.360
It tends to retract, you can't immobilize and get healing.

338
00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:26.550
So these are surgical cases,

339
00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:29.130
and we do wanna pay attention to this.

340
00:18:29.130 --> 00:18:31.800
If they're three weeks out, it's a done deal.

341
00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:34.830
There's no surgery to be done typically.

342
00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:38.370
You can't stretch that muscle back out

343
00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:40.500
to be able to reattach it.

344
00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:45.003
So we really want to get these individuals into the OR,

345
00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:48.270
the sooner the better

346
00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:50.853
but certainly within the first two weeks.

347
00:18:53.010 --> 00:18:54.360
A Boutonniere deformity,

348
00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:57.000
this is a central slip injury of the finger

349
00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.520
where the lateral extensor bands

350
00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:02.220
at the proximal interphalangeal joint,

351
00:19:02.220 --> 00:19:04.860
they sublux over the joint.

352
00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:06.330
They gradually pull

353
00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:10.020
that proximal interphalangeal joint into flexion

354
00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:13.020
and then subsequently the distal interphalangeal joint

355
00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:16.263
into extension or hyper extension,

356
00:19:18.450 --> 00:19:23.097
yeah, in kind of a hyperextension of the joint,

357
00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:25.350
the joint itself,

358
00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:30.350
even though the distal aspect comes into extension.

359
00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:32.820
So if I have this,

360
00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:35.370
and it takes time for these to develop,

361
00:19:35.370 --> 00:19:38.070
then what I do is I work at getting

362
00:19:38.070 --> 00:19:40.615
the proximal interphalangeal joint

363
00:19:40.615 --> 00:19:44.220
splinted into a neutral position

364
00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:47.790
or a straightened out position

365
00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:50.610
trying to get that flexion out of it.

366
00:19:50.610 --> 00:19:53.880
And this is a case where I'm gonna splint that joint

367
00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:55.140
for a period of time,

368
00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:58.110
and then I'm gonna follow it with night splinting

369
00:19:58.110 --> 00:19:59.640
for a period of time.

370
00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:01.410
And the last one's the mallet finger.

371
00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:02.820
And the mallet finger,

372
00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:05.880
I have avulsed that extensor digitorum tendon.

373
00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:07.620
We've all seen this.

374
00:20:07.620 --> 00:20:11.070
And so for these, I want to immobilize

375
00:20:11.070 --> 00:20:15.990
only the distal interphalangeal joint only

376
00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:20.990
in extension or hyperextension if I can a little bit,

377
00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:24.390
and I'm going to keep them fully immobilized

378
00:20:24.390 --> 00:20:27.810
for a period of six to eight weeks

379
00:20:27.810 --> 00:20:30.030
before I ever remove the splint.

380
00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:32.580
This is where if your patient comes back

381
00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:33.930
and they say, well, Doc,

382
00:20:33.930 --> 00:20:36.090
I changed this splint myself at home,

383
00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:37.470
and I took it off

384
00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:39.840
and then I did some things around the house,

385
00:20:39.840 --> 00:20:42.510
and then I put it back on.

386
00:20:42.510 --> 00:20:45.570
You're starting over from the time they did that, right?

387
00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:49.293
We reset the clock from that standpoint.

388
00:20:50.250 --> 00:20:53.940
Okay, this is for your clinical practice.

389
00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:55.620
You can print this out.

390
00:20:55.620 --> 00:20:59.010
You've got your finger injuries, your exam, management,

391
00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:01.110
and then if you have any referrals

392
00:21:01.110 --> 00:21:03.240
that we would make based upon that.

393
00:21:03.240 --> 00:21:06.313
Okay, so let's move ahead to another question.

394
00:21:06.313 --> 00:21:09.150
A 74-year-old female patient with hypertension,

395
00:21:09.150 --> 00:21:12.780
osteoporosis, and arthritis is seen for routine follow up.

396
00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.510
She notes an increase in her back pain about two months ago.

397
00:21:15.510 --> 00:21:18.630
She denies any trauma or associated symptoms.

398
00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:22.890
Her medications include a thiazide, a bisphosphonate,

399
00:21:22.890 --> 00:21:25.830
a proton pump inhibitor, and a non-steroidal.

400
00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:27.420
Her exam is unchanged

401
00:21:27.420 --> 00:21:30.840
other than some mild diffuse low back tenderness.

402
00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:32.973
You obtain this radiograph.

403
00:21:34.290 --> 00:21:37.850
So I'll give you a minute to look at this radiograph.

404
00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:47.553
She's had an increase in back pain about two months ago.

405
00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:52.620
Okay, so the question is,

406
00:21:52.620 --> 00:21:54.903
which of the following statements is correct?

407
00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:58.290
She has an increased mortality rate of 15%

408
00:21:58.290 --> 00:22:00.363
over those without this condition,

409
00:22:01.710 --> 00:22:04.683
she will need to be evaluated for multiple myeloma,

410
00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.673
this is going to require surgical intervention,

411
00:22:10.140 --> 00:22:13.263
or 20% of these remain undiagnosed.

412
00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:22.740
Okay, so the correct answer is A,

413
00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:24.570
and we're gonna go over this.

414
00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.590
This is a vertebral compression fracture at L1.

415
00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:31.350
So we want to pay attention,

416
00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:33.120
vertebral compression fractures

417
00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:36.420
because of the mechanics of the spine

418
00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:41.420
occur pretty consistently between T8 and L2 and then L4.

419
00:22:43.050 --> 00:22:46.290
Those are the vertebra that we're really looking at.

420
00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:50.220
Osteoporosis, osteoporosis, osteoporosis.

421
00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:53.370
And then the fourth leading cause is not osteoporosis,

422
00:22:53.370 --> 00:22:56.343
it's osteoporosis risk factors, okay?

423
00:22:57.270 --> 00:22:59.700
All right, so you have that.

424
00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:02.970
Not 20% of these remain undiagnosed,

425
00:23:02.970 --> 00:23:07.350
but 66 to 67% remain undiagnosed.

426
00:23:07.350 --> 00:23:08.490
Why?

427
00:23:08.490 --> 00:23:12.420
Because our elderly patients think chronic pain

428
00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:16.800
or pain is part of the normal aging process.

429
00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:20.280
So they tend not to bring this to your attention.

430
00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:21.990
They don't come in to say,

431
00:23:21.990 --> 00:23:24.420
oh, well you know, my back's been hurting more.

432
00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:28.590
Well, I'm getting old, I have aches and pains.

433
00:23:28.590 --> 00:23:30.810
This is just part of that process.

434
00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:35.370
And that's why so many of these are undiagnosed.

435
00:23:35.370 --> 00:23:39.480
Why do these individuals have higher mortality?

436
00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:41.820
Because when we have

437
00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:45.960
thoracic vertebral compression fractures particularly,

438
00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:50.960
we tend to have a bit more of kyphosis

439
00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:53.220
that develops over time.

440
00:23:53.220 --> 00:23:55.620
Again, you've seen this in your patients,

441
00:23:55.620 --> 00:23:58.740
and they develop restrictive pulmonary disease,

442
00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:01.860
and that's a problem, especially as we get older.

443
00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:04.590
And then some of these are gonna occur

444
00:24:04.590 --> 00:24:06.960
because there's underlying malignancy.

445
00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:11.340
So individuals with vertebral compression fractures,

446
00:24:11.340 --> 00:24:13.623
particularly elderly,

447
00:24:15.420 --> 00:24:18.873
have a higher risk of mortality than those without this.

448
00:24:19.960 --> 00:24:21.420
Okay, so what do we want to do

449
00:24:21.420 --> 00:24:23.550
with the vertebral compression fracture?

450
00:24:23.550 --> 00:24:25.230
These are really key points

451
00:24:25.230 --> 00:24:30.230
and I want you to know each one of these inside and out.

452
00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:31.560
You're gonna manage pain

453
00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:34.350
so you can get them moving as quickly as possible,

454
00:24:34.350 --> 00:24:36.780
hopefully within 24 hours.

455
00:24:36.780 --> 00:24:39.570
So if it's somebody that I have to admit to the hospital

456
00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:41.850
because they're in so much pain,

457
00:24:41.850 --> 00:24:45.120
I want to address that pain as quickly as possible

458
00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:46.720
so I can get them up and moving.

459
00:24:48.390 --> 00:24:50.730
This is the one place

460
00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:55.020
in an osteoporotic vertebral compression fracture,

461
00:24:55.020 --> 00:24:59.130
it's the one indication for the use of calcitonin.

462
00:24:59.130 --> 00:25:01.560
We use nasal calcitonin,

463
00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:05.283
gives moderately good pain relief.

464
00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:07.380
The second thing

465
00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:09.720
that I want you to pay attention to and know

466
00:25:09.720 --> 00:25:14.720
is that if I have an individual who has a fragility fracture

467
00:25:15.330 --> 00:25:17.610
and this vertebral compression fracture

468
00:25:17.610 --> 00:25:20.643
would count as a fragility fracture, no trauma,

469
00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:27.060
I'm postmenopausal female or a male over 70,

470
00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:30.570
and I sustain a vertebral compression fracture,

471
00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.180
you need to evaluate their bone health.

472
00:25:33.180 --> 00:25:35.193
And we do that by getting a DXA.

473
00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.410
And third, when we use bisphosphonates,

474
00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:43.680
we essentially put a five-year limit on our use.

475
00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:46.593
And that's a total limit over lifetime.

476
00:25:47.910 --> 00:25:50.490
Otherwise, as I go beyond that,

477
00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:54.810
I have marked increase in my atypical femoral fractures,

478
00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:57.360
particularly for these individuals.

479
00:25:57.360 --> 00:26:01.170
Okay, I do wanna mention pelvic insufficiency fractures

480
00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:03.180
because you also see these.

481
00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:06.960
It's again, osteoporosis, osteoporosis, osteoporosis

482
00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:09.030
are causes for these.

483
00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:12.003
Individuals who sit down a little too hard.

484
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.780
They may have missed the edge of the bed

485
00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:16.620
as they're sitting down,

486
00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:17.820
but they say, don't worry, Doc,

487
00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:20.640
I lowered myself down to the ground.

488
00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:22.650
And they come into the ER,

489
00:26:22.650 --> 00:26:25.710
they come in, or into our office in a wheelchair,

490
00:26:25.710 --> 00:26:28.260
but by the time we see them, examine them,

491
00:26:28.260 --> 00:26:31.260
and try and get them up to walk, they can't walk

492
00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:33.600
because it's too painful.

493
00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:36.690
Get radiographs for these individuals.

494
00:26:36.690 --> 00:26:41.690
If the radiographs are negative, but you still suspect this,

495
00:26:41.970 --> 00:26:45.450
or you have osteopenia on your radiographs,

496
00:26:45.450 --> 00:26:48.543
then you have to decide between a CT or a MRI.

497
00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:52.260
And a CT is good.

498
00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:55.350
I mean it's markedly better than radiographs.

499
00:26:55.350 --> 00:27:00.300
It's good, but you're just gonna have to make that decision.

500
00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:03.540
Do I need to wait a couple hours and get the MRI,

501
00:27:03.540 --> 00:27:06.450
or do I get the CT, and I'm done in 15 minutes?

502
00:27:06.450 --> 00:27:08.610
And you kind of have to decide,

503
00:27:08.610 --> 00:27:11.580
am I gonna have to admit this person in the first place?

504
00:27:11.580 --> 00:27:15.240
I've already gotta admit 'em, maybe I'll go with the CT,

505
00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:19.020
I'll presumptively make the diagnosis if the CT is negative.

506
00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:20.790
You just have to make those decisions.

507
00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:25.790
But remember, MRI is still the premier exam

508
00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:30.033
for osteoporotic pelvic insufficiency fractures.

509
00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:33.960
Think about getting a baseline hemoglobin when they come in,

510
00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:36.120
especially if you're admitting them,

511
00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:38.880
so that you can measure it the following day

512
00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:40.050
because they can put one

513
00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:43.500
or two units of blood here in the pelvis.

514
00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:45.870
So again, pay attention to that.

515
00:27:45.870 --> 00:27:49.500
Realize that you're immediately looking for subacute rehab

516
00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:51.870
or transitional care for these individuals

517
00:27:51.870 --> 00:27:56.010
because their average length of stay is 14 to 45 days

518
00:27:56.010 --> 00:27:58.440
before they can consider returning home.

519
00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:01.383
And again, work-up for osteoporosis.

520
00:28:02.280 --> 00:28:04.900
A few comments about hip fracture

521
00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:10.683
almost always caused by falling directly onto the hip.

522
00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:16.050
And not a surprise that it affects women more.

523
00:28:16.050 --> 00:28:18.330
Women live longer than men.

524
00:28:18.330 --> 00:28:22.500
Women have a higher rate of osteoporosis than men.

525
00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:24.030
And so here's the data.

526
00:28:24.030 --> 00:28:25.590
